  "prompt": "What is the meaning of Hanuman Chalisa?",
  "response": "The Hanuman Chalisa is a devotional hymn dedicated to Lord Hanuman, a central figure in Hindu mythology known for his strength, devotion, and loyalty. The term \"Chalisa\" refers to a composition of 40 verses (chalisa means \"forty\" in Hindi). The poem was written by the 16th-century poet Tulsidas, who is also known for his epic poem, the Ramcharitmanas.\n\nThe Hanuman Chalisa extols the virtues and exploits of Lord Hanuman, emphasizing his unwavering devotion to Lord Rama, his role in the Ramayana, and his qualities such as courage, humility, and selflessness. Reciting the Hanuman Chalisa is believed to bring strength, protection, and fulfillment of wishes, and it is often recited by devotees seeking blessings and guidance.\n\nOverall, the Hanuman Chalisa serves as a spiritual text that encourages devotion and reverence towards Hanuman, portraying him as a symbol of devotion, service, and the triumph of good over evil.",
